                      <font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Got a question here, 'cause I REALLY, REALLY suck at math. And I took Algebra , ermm about 15 years ago. <br /><br />I read that there are 2 million people waking up in prison. (That's 1 out of every 143 people in the U.S.A ) <br /><br />I read 96 percent of all cases that go to trial get plead down (from the context of the sentence, I assumed it meant "plead down so they don't end up in prison". <br /><br />I read that Ashcroft is saying he wants "maximum penalties" given ( I.E. Judges can't decide how long a person goes to Jail, he kind of whips out his card that says, Rape = 10 years,  XXX -  XXX years, etc. ) <br /><br />So, if everyone went to jail, how many people would there be in Jail? 50 million?<br /><br />Would you need more lawyers and cops, or less lawyers and cops? And Judges? More or less? <br /><br />Or would society even be able to function?<br /><br />It kind of blew that little candle out in me brain....<br /><br />I remember something I read before, that said "What if crime suddenly stopped?" <br /><br />What would happen to all those people, who just love to fuck other people up - on a daily basis- if they lost their job ?<br /><br />I bet they'd go insane and just sit there going, "SHUT UP KID SHUT UP KID SHUT UP KID SHUT UP KID " <br /><br /><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2003/LAW/08/15/findlaw.analysis.allenbaugh.sentencing/index.html" target="_blank">http://www.cnn.com/2003/LAW/08/15/findlaw.analysis.allenbaugh.sentencing/index.html</a><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span id="msg"></font>
