                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> The figure is indeed shocking, and it gets even worse when you start looking at particular profiles, ethnic or geographic (like almost one every 3 black males in the US has been or is in jail.... scary).<br />No this society is not liberal. As a metter of fact, living in the US is pretty down scary/oppressive, if you come from any European country. <br />The sad part about it, is that I do not believe this to be a result of different culture/ideology (well, sure, it is, but in minor part). Simply, I believe it to be a result of free markets, and of a privatized (or partially so) prison system. While in most of the rest of the world there is a clear interest in reducing prison populations to save the taxpayer's money, it seems that this "cost-saving" motivation falls here in second place. The lobbing attempts of the private companies managing prisons have been very effective in rising the number of people in prison, year after year. The present change, masked as a way of creating more fairness, is just another way this administration has to please its campaign contributors.<br /><br />Sadly, I see a similar trand in other places. The first pro-business, burgeous, government of Italy has passed two new laws last week:<br />- one reduces maximum sentences for money-laundering and tax evasion<br />- the other eliminated the distinctions between "light" and "heavy" drugs, mputting posession of heroin and weed on the same plate. <br />I can fucking see it. The Italian middle class, sitting in their houses, thinking of ways of making that extra, not exactly legal, buck, scared as all hell of that dangerous pot smoker that could come any minute in their house to rob them and rape their daughters.... Aren't they happy about our new government? <br />Same shit is happening in the US. Except worse, cause money is playing a bigger role.</span i