                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I agree on the fact that most Euro country are closer to the socialist ideal than the US. But I do not believe that inefficiency is necessary a product of a socialist system (you say those countries are "not very concerned with saving taxpayers money"... while that is often true for European countries, I believe it has nothing to do with the socialist orientation). <br />What I was trying to say is that, while there is only one force acting on the issue in most of the other countries (the desire to save money), there are two forces acting on it in the USA (on one side, the desire to diminish spending, to save people's money - on the other side, the desire to spend more to please party contributors, who happen to, between the other things, run jails --- now, do not get me wrong, if the system was honest than this would not be an issue, after all, a benefit for the few (the prison owners) should never outweight a plague for many (paying more taxes); but we can see the system is, indeed, corrupt, here like everywhere else. While that corruption manifests itself in other forms in other countries (building of thruways/bridges in Italy, hospitals in Greece, airports in Germany, just to mention few recent corruption stories) it does have an impact on the number of people in jail in the USA, while it has no affect on the prison population of other countries, where prisons are state-built/managed/owned). I bet you if prisons were to privatized in Italy, the local mafia would get the contracts, and next thing you know you would see people in jail for speeding tickets and parking infractions). <br /><br />After all, and please correct me if I am wrong, I am not aware of any other country privatizing jails. So what does that say:<br />- the USA is the only (mmm i guess, maybe I am wrong) country with private jails<br />- the USA puts more people in prison (per number of citizens, as well as overall) than any other place in the Western world. <br />Coincidence?</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
