                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">- the USA is the only (mmm i guess, maybe I am wrong) country with private jails <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Ummm...not exactly true.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">- the USA puts more people in prison (per number of citizens, as well as overall) than any other place in the Western world. <br />Coincidence?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Yes?<br /><br />Seriously.  The number of USA inmates in private prisons is a fairly small percentage of the total serving sentences.<br /><br />A lot of things contribute to the USA's higher incarceration rate.  In most western societies, TV news is a government run or subsidized service.  Here its a business with very high competition for ratings...so local news shows spend 80% of their time on crime news, giving Americans the impression that they live in a crime-ridden society.  The sad fact is, that with the exception of gun violence, USA crime rates are actually slightly below that of most large European countries.<br /><br />But most Americans are convinced by a steady TV diet of crime stories that society is spinning out of control.  So they support tougher sentencing policies than found elsewhere.  Offenders here are more likely to get caught, more likely to go to prison and more likely to get a long sentence.  <br /><br />In addition the USA does suffer from a lot more gun violence.  And such crimes are very likely to be solved, and tend to carry very long sentences.  People who commit murder or assaults with guns in the USA tend to spend a lot more time behiond bars than their European counterparts.  The disparity is even more extreme than it is for lesser crimes. Someone convicted of Second degree murder in the USA can expect to spend 20 years or more behind bars.  In Germany, its less than 8.  In Italy, its even lower.<br /><br />There are also more people serving sentences for drug possession in the USA.  But thats primarily because the illegal drug trade in the USA is porportionately larger, and because police here make trafficing a bigger enforcement priority.<br /><br />It all adds up.  But the dramatic rise in incarceration here has corresponded with fairly dramatic drops in crime rates, both against property and people.  So it appears to be 'working' at reducing crime.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
