                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">There is a huge difference between New York City and the states that borders Mexico<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Yep.<br /><br />But when it comes to crime the biggest difference is that the states that border Mexico have more "Southerners" living in them.<br /><br />The truth is that crime grew massively in US cities as they experienced mass migration from the rural South from the 1930s to the 1970s.  And the period of mass immigration from Mexico and other Third World countries has corresponded with DROPS in overall crime rates.<br /><br />/shrug<br /><br />I've lived in poor working-class neighborhoods of Mexican immigrants in Chicago, LA and Northern California, and never felt the least bit unsafe.  Unfortunately, I can't say the same about my experiences in poor white communities in Alabama and Louisiana.  Or a poor black neighborhood in Oakland.<br /><br />An apples and oranges comparison?  Hell no.  New York City's immigrant population is overwhelmingly drawn parts of the world a lot more violent than Mexico:  Jamaica, Haiti, Pakistan, Columbia, etc....OTOH, lots of the foreigners you find in New York moved there to get away from violence in their home country.<br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
