                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Do you have a source for your statement regarding south eastern heritage directly related to criminal activity? That seems as ridiculous as Dirth's "blame the ignorant foreigners" attack. While I do not mean to imply your statement is inaccurate it is, without some support, a little hard to swallow.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />The book "All God's Children, The Bosket Family and the American Tradition of Violence" by Fox Butterfield.  It won the Pullitzer Prize and the American Book award a few years back.<br /><br /><br />And its not so crazy when you look at the history of the USA Southeast.  It was heavily settled from what was the most primitive and violent part of Europe at the time, the Borderlands of England and Scotland.  Its economy was built around slave-based plantation agriculture for centuries, which was only reformed via a violent civil war that smashed the region flat. Afterwards the region experienced an extended period of racial and political violence, weak government, lynchings and general lawlessness.<br /><br />The entire political and and social system of the Southeast was built around extra-legal violence until well after WWII.  The history still shows through in crime statistics.    You can check any comprehensive historical comparative study of violent crime.  The American Southeast has been a comparatively violent place until very recently, especially in rural areas.  Parts of the Northeast, Midwest and West that did not experience heavy in-migration from the South have never experienced much violent crime.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
